### Problems of this chapter\
This chapter cleans up objections from various quarters that the view I have been developing about virtues, that they are acquired realizations of our potential, of humanity\'92s nature as practical, rational, animals. \
\
Some philosophers have objected to this kind of view as insufficiently \'91naturalistic.\'92 Others, strangely enough, have objected the other way that this kind of view is *too* naturalistic. \
\
James Lenman, for instance, faults not only Foot\'92s clarity but about her right to credentials of naturalism. Rehg does as well. \
