### Chris Toner, "Sorts of Naturalism"\
\
There is a distinction between some generic statement -- empirical, biological, metaphysical -- and the kind of statement that can serve as a reason. \
\
Christopher Toner attempts to draw out just this distinction.[@toner2008sorts] \
\
Toner agrees with Hursthouse that the term 'Aristotelian naturalism' "implies that human nature is normative, such that to be morally good is to fulfill one's nature."[@toner2008sorts 221.] Hursthouse and McDowell can confirm this reading: Hursthouse herself says that "Virtue ethics, or at least any form of it that takes its inspiration from Aristotle, is usually taken to be a form of ethical naturalism -- broadly, the enterprise of basing ethics in some way on consideration of human nature, on what is involved with being good *qua* human being."[@hursthouse1998 192] McDowell too believe that it is possible to "formulate a conception of reason that is, in one sense, naturalistic: a formed state of practical reason is one's second nature, not something that dictates to one's nature from outside."[@mcdowell1998two] However, Toner argues that Thompson\'92s, Hursthouse\'92s, and Foot\'92s brands of naturalism cannot adequately respond to a criticism McDowell (among others) have pressed. Toner presents four criteria that \'93naturalism must deliver if it is to support a revived Aristotelian virtue ethics\'85\'94[@toner2008sorts 222] \
\
\
Since we have already discussed each of these types of naturalism elsewhere, I shall only offer the briefest summaries \
