#### Thompson\
\
Thompson's naturalism is "an attempt to work out the special logic of judgments we make about living things, and then to indicate its application to ethics." That 'special logic' is variously called "natural-historical judgment", "Aristotelian categorical", and (we might add) "generics".[see @leslie2008generics for a discussion of generics in general; and see  @bailey2015animalism for a discussion of a specific generic: "we are animals".] I shall use my preferred term, the shorter and less adorned, \'93generic\'94. Many generics take the form \'93S is F\'94 or \'93S has or does F\'94. They are not true universals that can be translated rigorously as \'93for any x, if x is an S, then S is F\'94 nor are they mere existentials that can be translated as \'93for some x, if x is S, then S is F.\'94 Particular or existential statements like the latter are true but uninteresting. A generic is interesting because it is, or we treat it as, a truth about forms, or species. The subject of the statement is not all S\'92s nor merely some S\'92s, but the \'93infama species.\'94[@toner2008sorts 222, quoting Thompson] Such judgments \'93admit of combination into teleological judgments\'94 such as *penguins are countershaded in order to avoid predators from above and below.* Thompson insists that judgments about natural teleology are made true from the form of life under question, not from \'93hypotheses about the past\'94 (and Toner adds \'93whether about creation or natural selection\'94).[@toner2008sorts 223. Cf. (Thompson 1995, 293)] Since an individual penguin may fail to be countershaded in the way that expresses its form, it would be defective. This defect is not a judgment made by scientists and \'93imposed\'94 as it were, from the outside, on the penguin; but a normative fact about the penguin. \
