## MacIntyre on nature\
   \
For MacIntyre, who is allergic to metaphysics, he does not give a robust account of nature. He seems to assume a Laplacian picture of disenchanted nature in *Dependent Rational Animals*: nature which is a somewhat random bricolage of matter, energy, constants, wave functions, and so on, and somehow produces living organisms which through mutation and natural selection become creatures like us. \
\
## Foot on nature\
\
Foot\'92s picture of nature is friendly to the Aristotelian picture. Those parts of nature that constitute living organisms are characterized not only by their material origins, material parts, and material organization but also by their functions. \
\
## McDowell on nature\
\
McDowell\'92s picture of nature is radically dualistic. He too is allergic to metaphysics in the sense that he doesn\'92t take himself to be attempting to describe the world as it is \'93given.\'94 Rather, he sees humans as occupants of \'93second nature\'94 \'97 our receptivity to reasons is not \'93baldly natural.\'94 Animals do not have a second nature but only a primary nature. Bald nature, primary nature, is descriptive. It is a Laplacian picture. \
\
## Annas on Nature\
\
There are roughtly three options, Annas says: basing ethics on theories of nature, on non-natural properties (like goodness); or on religious or metaphysical theories. So, some virtue ethical theories are based on religious or metaphysical theories (Christian ethics, Platonic ethics). Other ethical theories (not necessarily virtue theories) treat 'the good' as sui generis, non-natural property. But naturalistic virtue ethics aims to position phrases like 'a good human' in conscious juxtaposition with 'a good plant' or 'a good penguin.'\
